🔑 DSA Pattern / Concept
Pattern: Greedy Range Expansion (a.k.a. BFS on array levels)

Why?

At each index, you can jump up to nums[i] steps.

You want the minimum jumps → think of it as levels in BFS.

Greedy strategy:

Track the current range you can reach with the current jump.

Expand to the farthest range possible.

When you exhaust the current range, increment jump count.

If you ever can’t move forward, return -1.

✅ Algorithm
Initialize jumps=0, currentEnd=0, farthest=0.

Traverse array from i=0 to n-2:

Update farthest = max(farthest, i + nums[i]).

If i == currentEnd:

Increment jumps.

Update currentEnd = farthest.

If currentEnd < i, return -1 (stuck).

At the end, if currentEnd >= n-1, return jumps. Otherwise, -1.

📌 Full C++ Code
cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T; cin >> T;
    while (T--) {
        int n; cin >> n;
        vector<int> nums(n);
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> nums[i];

        int jumps = 0, currentEnd = 0, farthest = 0;
        bool possible = true;

        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
            farthest = max(farthest, i + nums[i]);
            if (i == currentEnd) {
                jumps++;
                currentEnd = farthest;
                if (currentEnd <= i) { // stuck
                    possible = false;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }

        if (!possible || currentEnd < n - 1) cout << -1 << "\n";
        else cout << jumps << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
